{{Redirect|Orthodox Lutheran Conference|the denomination organized in 2006|Orthodox Lutheran Confessional Conference}} {{Infobox Christian denomination | name = Concordia Lutheran Conference | other_names = The Orthodox Lutheran Conference | image = | imagewidth = | alt = | caption = | main_classification = [[Lutheran]] | orientation = [[confessional Lutheran]] | polity = [[congregational]] | leader/moderator = | leader_title = President | leader_name = Rev. Edward J. Worley | fellowships = | associations = 7 mission stations in [[Russia]] and [[Nigeria]] | area = [[United States]], especially [[Illinois]], [[Washington (U.S. state)|Washington]], [[Oregon]], and [[Arizona]] | website = http://www.concordialutheranconf.com | founder = | founded_date = 1951, 1957 | founded_place = [[Okabena]], [[Minnesota]] | separated_from = [[Lutheran Church–Missouri Synod]] | absorbed = Fellowship of Lutheran Congregations (2004) | parent = | merger = | separations = | hospitals = | nursing_homes = | aid = | congregations = 6 | members = | ministers = 6 | missionaries = | temples = | primary_schools = | secondary_schools = | tertiary = | footnotes = }}{{Lutheranism in the United States|expanded=synodical}}
The '''Concordia Lutheran Conference''' is a small organization of Lutheran churches in the [[United States]] which formed in 1956.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Wuthnow|first1=Robert|title=The restructuring of American religion society and faith since World War II|date=1989|publisher=Princeton Univ. Press|location=Princeton, NJ|isbn=9780691020570|page=184|edition=2. print., and 1. Princeton pbk. print.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-ZPsISqdV5cC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref> It was a reorganization of some of the churches of the '''Orthodox Lutheran Conference''', which had been formed in September, 1951 in Okabena, Minnesota<ref>David Mensing, ''Historical Essays'', (Oak Forest, Illinois: Scriptural Publications, 2009), 3.</ref> following a break with [[Lutheran Church–Missouri Synod]]. It is the remaining successor of the Orthodox Lutheran Conference. The current president is the Reverend Edward J. Worley, pastor of St. Luke's Lutheran Church in Seattle, Washington. All members of the board of directors serve one year terms.<ref>{{cite web|title=CONSTITUTION of the CONCORDIA LUTHERAN CONFERENCE|url=http://www.concordialutheranconf.com/doctrine/constitution.cfm|website=www.concordialutheranconf.com|accessdate=8 December 2014|location=ARTICLE XI -- TERM OF OFFICE|quote=Officers and members of standing committees shall be elected to hold office for one year}}</ref> It is in fellowship with 7 mission congregations in [[Russia]] and [[Nigeria]].
Scriptural Publications, the publishing arm of the Concordia Lutheran Conference, has just published an anthology, ''Historical Essays'' by Rev. David T. Mensing: "The Missouri Synod's Slide into Heterodoxy, 1932-1947"; "The Establishment of Heterodoxy in the Missouri Synod, 1950"; and "The Founding of the Orthodox Lutheran Conference, 1951".
==History== In 2004, the CLC absorbed the congregations of the '''Fellowship of Lutheran Congregations'''. The FLC was organized in 1979, when a group of Lutheran congregations left the [[Lutheran Churches of the Reformation]] over issues of excommunication.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.concordialutheranconf.com/2015/07/02/iintroducing-the-pastors-of-the-f-l-c-n/|title=Introducing The Pastors of The F. L. C. N.|last=Mensing|first=David T.|date=July 2, 2015|website=Concordia Lutheran Conference|publisher=The Concordia Lutheran|access-date=March 31, 2018}}</ref>
==Teachings== The Conference describes itself as "orthodox," with special emphasis on the inerrant, literal interpretation of the Christian [[Bible]]. The Concordia Lutheran Conference subscribes to the [[Book of Concord]] and the ''Brief Statement of the Doctoral Position of the Missouri Synod'' in its doctrinal stance.
==Purpose== The Conference is a gathering of churches to engage in tasks that would be hard for any one church to perform.<ref name=WhatIsClC>{{cite web|title=What is the Concordia Lutheran Conference?|url=http://www.concordialutheranconf.com/|website=concordialutheranconf.com|accessdate=19 March 2015}}</ref> This includes the training of future pastors in their seminary program.<ref name=WhatIsClC />
