{{Infobox Christian denomination |name = United Lutheran Mission Association |image = |imagewidth = |caption = |main_classification = [[Lutheran]] |orientation = [[Confessional Lutheran]] |theology = [[Conservatism|conservative]] |polity = [[Congregationalist polity|Congregationalist]] |structure = |leader = |headquarters = [[Decatur, Illinois]] |founder = |founded_date = July 16, 2005 |founded_place = [[Chicago, Illinois]] |separated_from = [[Lutheran Church–Missouri Synod]] |merger = |separations = |associations = |area = [[United States]], [[California]], [[Illinois]], [[Michigan]], [[Virginia]]. |congregations = 3 |members = |website = [http://www.unitedlutheranmission.org www.unitedlutheranmission.org] |footnotes = }} {{Lutheranism in the United States|expanded=synodical}} The '''United Lutheran Mission Association''' ('''ULMA''') is a [[Lutheranism|Lutheran]] church organization.
==History== The '''United Lutheran Mission Association''' was established at a meeting in [[Chicago]] on July 16, 2005. There, representatives of two congregations that were formerly members of the [[Lutheran Church–Missouri Synod]] (LCMS), namely, Pilgrim Lutheran Church of [[Decatur, Illinois]] and Redeemer Lutheran Church of [[St. Clair Shores, Michigan]], began work on establishing [[Confessional Lutheran]] congregations in the United States. A third congregation, Our Redeemer Lutheran Church of [[Forsyth, Illinois]], joined on December 15, 2011. As of 2013, the ULMA has two mission congregations: Agnus Dei in [[Fredericksburg, Virginia]], whose first service was in December, 2007; and Christ the Rock Lutheran Church of [[Carlsbad, California]], whose first service was February 8, 2009.
==Structure== The ULMA, like the [[Protes'tant Conference]], is congregationalist in polity. The voters assembly is the supreme authority in the congregation. There is no central office or centralized organizational structure other than the individual representatives who meet twice each year. The ULMA plans to train its own pastors at [[Walther Theological Seminary]], but as of 2014 has had no graduates.<ref>https://groups.yahoo.com/neo/groups/unitedlutheranmission/conversations/topics/97</ref> The ULMA has obtained clergy trained in the seminaries of other Lutheran denominations, such as the LCMS, the [[Wisconsin Evangelical Lutheran Synod]], and the [[Evangelical Lutheran Synod]].
